<Folder><name>Sahel Core</name><open>0</open>
<Placemark><name>🇧🇫 Burkina Faso — JNIM Insurgency + Military Overreach</name>
<description><![CDATA[<b>Burkina Faso — JNIM Insurgency + Military Overreach</b><br/><b>Subregion:</b> Sahel Core<br/><b>Category:</b> MILITARY | <b>Domain:</b> Jihadist Insurgency / State Atrocity<br/><b>Severity:</b> CRITICAL | <b>Status:</b> ESCALATING<br/><b>Index:</b> 93/100 (Δ ±0)<br/><b>Human cost:</b> 50% of all Sahel militant-Islamist deaths; Djibo/Barsalogho massacres<br/><b>Note:</b> NEW STANDALONE · Burkina = highest violence in Sahel (50% of regional militant deaths, Africa Center) · JNIM briefly SEIZED Djibo + Diapaga (May) · ~90 soldiers killed Koubel-Alpha ambush · CRITICAL: Burkinabè troops caused 56% of civilian fatalities Jan23-Mar26 (ACLED) — more than jihadists · IPC Phase 4 famine risk · JNIM displayed photo of Ouagadougou · NEW: JNIM attacked Dargo base (~50 soldiers killed) + pressuring Fada N'Gourma western approaches to isolate it from Ouagadougou · Fada University raid<br/><b>Gov sources:</b> Burkina Defense/Justice Ministries: Non-responsive to HRW inquiries; dissolved political parties; entrenched military rule via new fundamental law | US State Dept: Senior official Nick Checker visited Ouagadougou (Mar 2026) to 'relaunch relations'<br/><b>Mil leverage:</b> JNIM: Territorial control + Djibo siege (5+ yrs); urban ambitions; recruitment from army abuses [HIGH] | IS-Sahel (ISGS): Outbidding rival; convoy/aid attacks (Gorom Gorom) [MED] | Traoré junta + VDP + Africa Corps: Air power but VDP militia gutted; can't hold territory [LOW] | Russia (Africa Corps): Limited scope; fuel-convoy escort only [LOW]<br/><b>Assessment:</b> Burkina Faso enters as its own theater at 93 — the Sahel's epicenter. The defining dynamic, per ACLED, is the vicious cycle: the army kills more civilians than the jihadists do, which drives recruitment, which the junta answers with more force. The VDP militia that was central to Traoré's mobilization has been gutted. JNIM's seizure of Djibo and Diapaga and its display of Ouagadougou signal a shift from rural insurgency toward urban ambitions — the trajectory to watch.<br/><i>v15.0 · Week 12</i>]]></description><styleUrl>#s-military</styleUrl>
