<Placemark><name>🇲🇱 Mali — JNIM Economic Warfare + FLA/Azawad</name>
<description><![CDATA[<b>Mali — JNIM Economic Warfare + FLA/Azawad</b><br/><b>Subregion:</b> Sahel Core<br/><b>Category:</b> MILITARY | <b>Domain:</b> Jihadist Insurgency / Economic Siege<br/><b>Severity:</b> CRITICAL | <b>Status:</b> ESCALATING<br/><b>Index:</b> 92/100 (Δ +1)<br/><b>Human cost:</b> 29% of Sahel militant deaths; 207 JNIM deaths Jan-Apr; Defense Min Camara killed<br/><b>Note:</b> JUL 1: JNIM launched SEVEN coordinated attacks across Ségou + Kayes regions incl. Kayes city itself — region home to ~80% of Mali's industrial gold production, previously largely spared · army claims 80+ militants killed; JNIM claims dozens of soldiers + 100+ vehicles + governor's residence damage (DISPUTED figures) · JNIM threatened Kayes/Nioro blockade next day · Crisis Group: testing urban defenses, aiming to "encourage the regime's collapse from within" · 245,000+ Malian refugees now in Mauritania (~5% of its population)<br/><b>Gov sources:</b> Mali Armed Forces General Staff: Confirmed Apr 25 coordinated attacks 'by unidentified armed terrorist groups'; Foreign Min Diop calls ECOWAS exit 'final' | US/UK Embassies: Urged citizens to 'depart immediately'; pulled diplomatic staff (Oct 2025) | Mali Education Ministry: Ordered schools shut Oct 26-Nov 9 due to blockade | Mali Armed Forces: Claims 80+ militants killed repelling the Jul 1 seven-site assault (figures disputed by JNIM claims) | Mauritania Government: 245,000+ Malian refugees registered — equivalent to ~5% of Mauritania's population<br/><b>Mil leverage:</b> JNIM: Bamako fuel blockade — economic siege of the capital; 6,000 fighters; taxes/governance [HIGH] | FLA (Azawad Liberation Front): Seized Kidal; structured JNIM alliance; northern control [HIGH] | Goïta junta + Africa Corps: Su-24 airstrikes, drones; but withdrew from Kidal region [MED] | Coastal neighbors (Senegal/CI): 95% of Mali fuel transits their routes — chokepoint leverage [MED]<br/><b>Econ leverage:</b> JNIM (Commodity + corridor) [HIGH]: Kayes region = ~80% of industrial gold output, now under attack; 95% of fuel transits Senegal/CI corridors JNIM blockades<br/><b>Assessment:</b> Mali rises to 92. The July 1 Kayes strike is a strategic marker: seven simultaneous attacks hundreds of kilometers apart, hitting the region that produces ~80% of Mali's industrial gold and anchors the Senegal trade corridor. Crisis Group reads it as JNIM testing urban defenses and trying to induce regime collapse from within — the urban phase declared in 2024 is now operational. A DISPUTED single-source claim of Ukrainian involvement in coordinating April's attacks (likely info-op) is logged but not credited.<br/><i>v15.0 · Week 12</i>]]></description><styleUrl>#s-military</styleUrl>
