<Placemark><name>🇳🇪 Niger — ISSP + JNIM + Kidnapping Hub</name>
<description><![CDATA[<b>Niger — ISSP + JNIM + Kidnapping Hub</b><br/><b>Subregion:</b> Sahel Core<br/><b>Category:</b> MILITARY | <b>Domain:</b> Jihadist Insurgency<br/><b>Severity:</b> CRITICAL | <b>Status:</b> ESCALATING<br/><b>Index:</b> 88/100 (Δ ±0)<br/><b>Human cost:</b> 17% of Sahel militant deaths; Kirtachi 12 soldiers killed + 7 captured<br/><b>Note:</b> NEW STANDALONE · ISSP + JNIM outbidding · JNIM overran Kirtachi National Guard camp (12 killed, 7 captured) · ISSP hit Niamey Airport (Jan) + Tahoua Airport (Mar) + Niger-Benin oil pipeline sabotage · record Westerner kidnapping hub · Tiani dissolved parties, 5-yr transition to 2030 · ISSP leader Souleymane Ag Bakawa arrested by Mali/Africa Corps (Ménaka)<br/><b>Gov sources:</b> Niger Government: Confirmed AES Unified Force 'intense air campaigns' after Apr 25; accuses France of sponsoring attacks; cancelled May 1 parades for security | Tiani transitional decree: Dissolved all political parties (Mar 2025); 5-year transitional mandate to 2030<br/><b>Mil leverage:</b> ISSP (IS Sahel): Airport strikes; pipeline sabotage; kidnapping outsourcing; Nigeria-border bridge [HIGH] | JNIM: Kirtachi camp seizure; western Niger expansion [MED] | Tiani junta + Africa Corps: AES Unified Force air campaigns; capital defense (failing) [LOW] | Niger-Benin pipeline: Oil-export lifeline — a sabotage target = economic leverage [MED]<br/><b>Assessment:</b> Niger enters at 88. It is the ISSP stronghold to Mali/Burkina's JNIM core, and the JNIM-ISSP outbidding competition is driving both toward higher-impact attacks (airports, pipelines, kidnappings). Tiani's extension to 2030 confirms the coup's justification — that juntas would restore security — has not been met. The Nigeria-border bridge is the key expansion vector.<br/><i>v15.0 · Week 12</i>]]></description><styleUrl>#s-military</styleUrl>
