<Folder><name>Coastal Frontier</name><open>0</open>
<Placemark><name>🇧🇯🇹🇬 Benin &amp; Togo — JNIM Coastal Expansion</name>
<description><![CDATA[<b>Benin &amp; Togo — JNIM Coastal Expansion</b><br/><b>Subregion:</b> Coastal Frontier<br/><b>Category:</b> MILITARY | <b>Domain:</b> Jihadist Spillover<br/><b>Severity:</b> HIGH | <b>Status:</b> ESCALATING<br/><b>Index:</b> 72/100 (Δ ±0)<br/><b>Human cost:</b> Benin 305 deaths (+76%, record); Togo 54 civ + 8 soldiers<br/><b>Note:</b> NEW · Crisis Group: Benin + Togo 'in greatest peril' · Benin 305 militant deaths = deadliest on record (+76%) · JNIM appointed an EMIR for Benin · Koualou attack (disputed Benin-Burkina border) · Togo: Kpendjal Prefecture worst-hit, 54 civ killed · 450+ incidents/yr within 50km of coastal borders<br/><b>Gov sources:</b> Togo Government: Established one of the sub-region's most important security systems in the north; Cinkassé/Kpendjal front lines | Benin Government: Military positions at Koualou attacked; disputed border zone with Burkina Faso | AES-ECOWAS (Togo-mediated): Togo FM Dussey offered to 'bridge' AES and ECOWAS — first formal interaction since May 2025<br/><b>Mil leverage:</b> JNIM: Appointed Benin emir; deliberate strategic expansion (not spillover); border-zone control [HIGH] | Benin/Togo states: Militarized north; refugee-vetting (Ivorian model); regional coordination [MED] | Coastal ports: Landlocked-Sahel dependence = leverage over AES fuel/trade [MED]<br/><b>Assessment:</b> Benin and Togo enter as a clustered coastal-frontier theater at 72 — the leading edge of JNIM's southward push toward the Gulf of Guinea. Crisis Group names them 'in greatest peril.' The appointment of a Benin emir and the record death tolls mark the transition from spillover to a deliberate coastal campaign. This is the frontier to watch for whether the Sahel war reaches the Atlantic.<br/><i>v15.0 · Week 12</i>]]></description><styleUrl>#s-military</styleUrl>
