<Placemark><name>🇨🇮 Côte d'Ivoire — Contained Frontier</name>
<description><![CDATA[<b>Côte d'Ivoire — Contained Frontier</b><br/><b>Subregion:</b> Coastal Frontier<br/><b>Category:</b> MILITARY | <b>Domain:</b> Contained Spillover<br/><b>Severity:</b> MEDIUM | <b>Status:</b> STALEMATE<br/><b>Index:</b> 54/100 (Δ ±0)<br/><b>Human cost:</b> Grand-Bassam 2016 (19 killed); attacks halted 2020-21<br/><b>Note:</b> NEW · Managed to HALT attacks 2020-21 (the coastal success case) · prefect-led refugee vetting + registration model praised by analysts · remains vulnerable to JNIM rear-base use · Burkina-CI tensions (Traoré accuses Abidjan of undermining) · military containment + development combo<br/><b>Gov sources:</b> Ivorian Government: Local prefects vet incoming refugees + register displaced families to prevent infiltration — model cited by ISS/analysts | Military containment: Northern border force posture; combined with socio-economic development programs<br/><b>Mil leverage:</b> Ivorian state: Prefect refugee-vetting model; halted attacks; military+development combo [MED] | JNIM: Rear-base/logistics use of northern CI; Kafolo-area presence [MED] | Burkina Faso junta: Accuses CI of harboring dissidents — cross-border friction [MED]<br/><b>Econ leverage:</b> United States (Portfolio securities) [LOW]: $1.6B US securities (2025 TIC), mostly debt<br/><b>Assessment:</b> Côte d'Ivoire enters at 54 as the containment counter-model — proof the coastal advance is not inevitable. Its prefect-vetting approach is cited across the analyst literature as the template Ghana, Benin, and Togo are urged to adopt. The risk is less internal insurgency than becoming collateral to Burkina Faso's instability and JNIM's rear-base needs.<br/><i>v15.0 · Week 12</i>]]></description><styleUrl>#s-military</styleUrl>
