<Placemark><name>🇳🇬 Nigeria — ISWAP + Ansaru + Bandits + IPOB</name>
<description><![CDATA[<b>Nigeria — ISWAP + Ansaru + Bandits + IPOB</b><br/><b>Subregion:</b> Central Africa<br/><b>Category:</b> MILITARY | <b>Domain:</b> Multi-Threat Insurgency<br/><b>Severity:</b> HIGH | <b>Status:</b> ESCALATING<br/><b>Index:</b> 68/100 (Δ ±0)<br/><b>Human cost:</b> Tumfa airstrike: Amnesty alleges 100+ civilians; Niger/Kwara fatalities doubled<br/><b>Note:</b> UPDATED · JNIM claimed its FIRST Nigeria attacks (killed soldiers, Kwara/Niger border) · Ansaru re-emergence (AQIM/JNIM-allied), shifted to Kwara/Niger States · Lakurawa (ISGS-linked) in Kebbi/Sokoto, cooperating w/ Boko Haram Sadiku faction · ISWAP officer-killings (5 in 5 months) · banditry = most armed violence in NW<br/><b>Gov sources:</b> Nigerian Armed Forces: Multi-front operations; to embed journalists to improve security reporting; requested French support | US/France: ISR + Lakurawa precision airstrikes; deepening security footprint | CBN / NUPRC: FX reform + petroleum licensing — economic stability layer<br/><b>Mil leverage:</b> ISWAP / IS: Drones; officer-targeting; Niger-Nigeria bridge linking ISSP+ISWAP [HIGH] | JNIM + Ansaru: First Nigeria attacks; Kwara/Niger forest bases near Benin border [MED] | Bandits (NW): Most armed violence in NW; kidnap-for-ransom economy [MED] | Nigerian state: Dangote refinery, CBN FX reform, state-policing framework [MED]<br/><b>Econ leverage:</b> United States (Portfolio securities) [MED]: $8.0B US securities (2025 TIC; 3→8 over decade); mostly long-term debt, equity &lt;$0.5B<br/><b>Assessment:</b> Nigeria rises to 68. It is the hinge where the Sahel and Lake Chad theaters are fusing: JNIM's first Nigeria strikes, Ansaru's revival, and the Lakurawa-Boko Haram cooperation all point to a merging jihadi geography across the Niger-Nigeria border. The four-front problem (ISWAP, Sahel-linked groups, bandits, IPOB/ESN) makes Nigeria the most multi-dimensional theater in West Africa.<br/><i>v15.0 · Week 12</i>]]></description><styleUrl>#s-military</styleUrl>
