<Placemark><name>🇨🇴 Colombia — Rightward Rupture + US Collision</name>
<description><![CDATA[<b>Colombia — Rightward Rupture + US Collision</b><br/><b>Subregion:</b> South America<br/><b>Category:</b> POLITICAL | <b>Domain:</b> Electoral Rupture / Security Pivot<br/><b>Severity:</b> HIGH | <b>Status:</b> VOLATILE<br/><b>Index:</b> 66/100 (Δ ±0)<br/><b>Human cost:</b> Election-night clashes in Cali; armed-group coercion reported in rural areas<br/><b>Note:</b> NEW THEATER (backfilled) · MAY 31 first round: Espriella 43.7% / Cepeda 40.9% · JUN 21 runoff: Espriella 49.66% vs 48.70% (~250k votes; 63.6% turnout; 12.9M votes = most in Colombian history) · certified Jun 24; Cepeda conceded; Petro alleged fraud/foreign interference but recognized results · INAUGURATION AUG 7 · pledges: 90-day military offensive, 10 Bukele-style mega-prisons, fracking, end peace talks, Israel ties + Jerusalem embassy · pre-arc: DEA named Petro \'priority target\', US sanctioned him · DISPUTED: worker-coercion complaints (59 companies), armed-group pressure, AtlasIntel poll suspension<br/><b>Gov sources:</b> Registraduría / CNE: Certified Jun 24: 49.66% vs 48.70%; 63.6% turnout; AtlasIntel polls suspended May 19 over methodology (probe ongoing) | US State (Rubio) / Trump: Endorsement + 'Colombia's best days are ahead'; earlier sanctioned Petro; DEA priority-target designation | Colombia Ombudsman / Min. of Labor: Pre-election warnings on armed-group coercion; complaints from workers of 59 companies alleging vote coercion<br/><b>Mil leverage:</b> Espriella (from Aug 7): Trump endorsement + mandate for force; 12.9M votes but razor margin + divided Congress [MED] | United States: Sanctions precedent on Petro; DEA targeting; tariff/decert threats — hemisphere's template case [HIGH] | Armed groups (ELN/dissidents/Clan del Golfo): Expected to strike back at the 90-day offensive; rural electoral coercion already shown [MED] | Petro camp: 48.7% opposition bloc + fraud narrative; street mobilization capacity [MED]<br/><b>Assessment:</b> Colombia enters at 66, trend up toward the August 7 inauguration — the next hard calendar item after Iran's July cliffs and Sudan's July 7. The theater's core tension: a mandate for maximum force delivered by a minimum margin, against armed groups with proven capacity to answer offensives, under a US administration that has already shown (Venezuela) what the Donroe Doctrine permits. The 90-day offensive's first weeks will set the escalation curve.<br/><i>v15.0 · Week 12</i>]]></description><styleUrl>#s-political</styleUrl>
