<Placemark><name>🇺🇸 US Foreign Policy — Strikes + Brokerage</name>
<description><![CDATA[<b>US Foreign Policy — Strikes + Brokerage</b><br/><b>Subregion:</b> North America<br/><b>Category:</b> POLITICAL | <b>Domain:</b> Geopolitical Strategy<br/><b>Severity:</b> HIGH | <b>Status:</b> VOLATILE<br/><b>Index:</b> 64/100 (Δ +1)<br/><b>Human cost:</b> N/A<br/><b>Note:</b> Struck Iran (10 targets) + brokered Lebanon + Doha Jun 30 · UAE arms-sale fork on Sudan · African visa-embassy drawdown · DONROE DOCTRINE: post-Maduro corollary asserting right to intervene at will in Western Hemisphere — Venezuela occupied-by-leverage, Mexico indictments, Colombia election endorsement, Cuba strangulation · Congress notified of "non-international armed conflict" with cartels<br/><b>Gov sources:</b> US State Dept: 3 mediation tracks (Doha, Lebanon, Sudan-Boulos); African visa-processing drawdown | US CENTCOM: 10-target Iran strike<br/><b>Mil leverage:</b> White House: Strike power + $300B gatekeeping + arms sales + multi-track mediation [HIGH] | Congress (Graham): War Powers; UAE arms conditioning [MED] | Truth Social: Real-time signaling that moves events [MED]<br/><b>Assessment:</b> US foreign policy holds at 63 — striking Iran while running three mediation tracks. The central tension: US leverage over the UAE is the most effective unused lever on Sudan, yet the UAE is needed for the Iran coalition. Volatile stays right.<br/><i>v15.0 · Week 12</i>]]></description><styleUrl>#s-political</styleUrl>
