<Placemark><name>🔭 Maritime Chokepoints — Hormuz Managed-Access</name>
<description><![CDATA[<b>Maritime Chokepoints — Hormuz Managed-Access</b><br/><b>Subregion:</b> Global<br/><b>Category:</b> STRATEGIC | <b>Domain:</b> Maritime Security<br/><b>Severity:</b> HIGH | <b>Status:</b> VOLATILE<br/><b>Index:</b> 67/100 (Δ +2)<br/><b>Human cost:</b> N/A<br/><b>Note:</b> Iran formalized Hormuz claim (Qalibaf: sovereignty "lies with Iran and Oman"; joint administration + fees after 60-day MOU) · HOUTHIS RESUMED Red Sea attacks after months-long hiatus — SANK TWO commercial ships, vowed to expand to all Israel-bound vessels · Bab el-Mandeb reactivating as second stressed chokepoint · IRIB: foreign container ship ran aground off Iran-designated route<br/><b>Gov sources:</b> Iran FM Araghchi: Warns against 'separate arrangements'; claims sole Hormuz control | US/GCC/Oman: Reject any Iranian toll/control claim<br/><b>Mil leverage:</b> Iran: Hormuz — strike + 'governed by Iran' doctrine + sole-demining + route designation [HIGH] | US 5th Fleet: Escort + strike; can't compel safety [MED] | France/Oman: Demining offer — rejected by Iran [LOW] | Houthis/China: Bab el-Mandeb + Taiwan Strait (rising) [MED]<br/><b>Assessment:</b> Chokepoints ease to 65 as the stand-down restored transit, but the structure hardened: Iran demonstrated and doctrinally asserted managed access. Doha Jun 30 takes up Hormuz management — the most consequential maritime negotiation on the board.<br/><i>v15.0 · Week 12</i>]]></description><styleUrl>#s-strategic</styleUrl>
