<Placemark><name>🔭 Geopolitical Blocs — AES / Gulf / China-Cuba</name>
<description><![CDATA[<b>Geopolitical Blocs — AES / Gulf / China-Cuba</b><br/><b>Subregion:</b> Global<br/><b>Category:</b> STRATEGIC | <b>Domain:</b> Strategic Competition<br/><b>Severity:</b> WATCH | <b>Status:</b> WATCH<br/><b>Index:</b> 60/100 (Δ ±0)<br/><b>Human cost:</b> N/A — analytical + intelligence layer<br/><b>Note:</b> UPDATED · AES Confederation as sovereignty bloc: 15,000 Unified Force, joint passport/bank, 0.5% import levy, quit ECOWAS, reciprocal US travel-ban response · Gulf = $6B custodian + Doha venue + $300B · Bejucal SIGINT · OTS-Hungary · AES condemnation of US over Venezuela/Maduro now has full context: the Jan 3 capture + Donroe Doctrine — Pan-African + Latin American sovereignty pushback converging<br/><b>Gov sources:</b> AES communiqués: Unified Force launch (Dec 2025); import levy; reciprocal US travel ban; condemned US over Venezuela/Maduro | ISS Africa / Amani Africa: AES financing via national funds; central question is funding the force without donors | AU Peace &amp; Security Council: June 2026 review; late-response critique; AES-ECOWAS Abuja engagement<br/><b>Mil leverage:</b> AES (Mali/Burkina/Niger): 15,000 Unified Force; resource sovereignty (uranium/gold); anti-French realignment; Russia ties [HIGH] | Qatar/GCC: $6B custodian + Doha venue + $300B capital + toll rejection [HIGH] | China: Bejucal SIGINT (contested) + BRI + Cuba + rare earths; 53-country zero-tariff [MED] | Hungary (OTS): Russia-ally to EU-accession enabler pivot [MED]<br/><b>Econ leverage:</b> AES bloc (Sovereign funds + levy) [MED]: 0.5% import levy + national support funds financing the 15,000 Unified Force without donors<br/><b>Assessment:</b> The strategic layer rises to 60 with the AES added as a formal sovereignty bloc — the political-strategic counterpart to the Sahel-core military theaters. Its resource-sovereignty doctrine and anti-French realignment are consolidating institutionally even as the security justification for the coups goes unmet. The Gulf remains the decisive swing hinge of the Iran settlement.<br/><i>v15.0 · Week 12</i>]]></description><styleUrl>#s-strategic</styleUrl>
